JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1969
EP  - 1995
VL  - 58
IS  - 5
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1540-6261.00594
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract The fragility of the CAPM has led to a resurgence of research that frequently uses trading strategies based on sorting procedures to uncover relations between firm characteristics (such as ?value? or ?glamour?) and equity returns. We examine the propensity of these strategies to generate statistically and economically significant profits due to our familiarity with the data. Under plausible assumptions, data snooping can account for up to 50 percent of the in-sample relations between firm characteristics and returns uncovered using single (one-way) sorts. The biases can be much larger if we simultaneously condition returns on two (or more) characteristics.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Corporate Board Composition, Protocols, and Voting Behavior: Experimental Evidence
